- [X] Support tuple of axes for reductions

## P2

- [ ] Per-kernel WASM optimization levels (ReleaseSmall vs ReleaseFast)
    - ReleaseSmall saves ~73% binary size but regresses loop-bound kernels 40-166%
    - Compute-heavy kernels (matmul +3%, inner +8%) barely regress and are good candidates
    - Loop-bound kernels (lexsort, power, flip, count_nonzero) must stay ReleaseFast
    - Steps:
        1. Build a benchmark harness that compiles each kernel in both modes and compares perf
        2. Produce a per-kernel optimization map from the results
        3. Validate the map across runtimes (Node/Deno/Bun) to ensure consistency
        4. Update `build-wasm.ts` to accept per-kernel optimization overrides

- [ ] Implement async functions using Web Workers to avoid blocking main thread
- [ ] Reach 100% function coverage via unit and validation tests
- [ ] Reach >95% branch coverage via unit and validation tests
- [ ] Reach >95% statement coverage via unit and validation tests
- [ ] Simplify docs Quickstart
- [ ] Fix PR benchmark regression testing CI
- [X] Make all seeded `random` functions match NumPy's output byte-for-byte

